My question is: How do you give a table a picture border? (see <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://well-of-souls.com/feena/">here</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, the blue bubbly border surrounding the white table)<br>
<br>
Can this be done easily with notepad, or should I use dreamweaver or something similar?<br>
It's just that I feel the the tables on my website have rather boring edges, and I was planning on doing a sort of gold frame around them. Any help would be much appreciated <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upuhead.showPublicProfile?language=EN>puhead</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/23/01 11:29:35 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://pu.mordea.com/misc/bbsicon03.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: HTML - Tables question</span><hr size=1> Oh, that's easy.<br>
<br>
It's not actually html they're using to make the borders, those are images.<br>
What you can do is use ImageReady to splice images up so that they fit nice and snug when you piece individual pieces of the picture together.<br>
The borders are most likely made in photoshop, so it's not an html trick.<br>
<br>
But from what I see (much like what I do for my site) you make a table with 9 cells.<br>
3 rows<br>
3 columns<br>
(you can change em depending on the way you set yours up)<br>
<br>
On the corner cells, you would insert the respective corner image. The top middle and bottom middle cells would contain the horizontal border images, and the left and right middle would contain the left and right border images. The middle cell of the entire table would of course be the content, or the &quot;white part&quot; you're referring to.<br>
<br>
This can all be done using notepad, so there's no worries there. It's just a matter of aligning the images correctly and making sure your table calculations are correct.<br>
<br>
If you're really stuck, just view the source code on that webpage. Don't steal it though <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Just look at it, and hopefully figure it out.<br>
<br>
Tables are complicated to understand at first, but they get easy after a while.<br>
